Final example

Lets work through a sports example since its March Madness and my bracket is already busted.

Background: I went to Marquette Univeristy and my Freshman year was Jimmy Butlers final season (the 2010-11 season was awesome!)

So this is the data well work with:

Some of this example will work through this template from Matt Waite at NICAR 2019: https://mattwaite.github.io/nicar19/CourseMaterials.html

  • data: All team game logs for the 2018-19 season

All datasets sourced from Sports Reference.

Marquette data for the 2010-2011 season:

  • College basketball gamelogs for Marquette Universitys 2010-11 season.

And the game logs for each individual player: + Darius Johson-Odom + Jimmy Butler + Jae Crowder + Dwight Buycks + Chris Otule + Vander Blue + Davante Gardner + Junior Cadougan + Joe Fulce + Erik Williams + Jamail Jones + Reggie Smith + Robert Frozena

Clean, analyze and visualize these datasets. To do that well work with Rs tidyverse library.

Now lets combine and clean each of the players gamelog data from Marquette Universitys 2010-11 roster:

# run each group of functions separately

odom <- read_csv("mu-players/djo-1011.csv")

#TIP: can re-export a csv updated with name column to replace current one if needed

mu_players <- merge(odom, butler, all=TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., crowder, all = TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., buycks, all = TRUE) %>%
  merge(., otule, all = TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., blue, all = TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., gardner, all = TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., cadougan, all = TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., fulce, all = TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., williams, all = TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., jones, all = TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., smith, all = TRUE) %>% 
  merge(., frozena, all = TRUE)

# rename some columns and filter out each player's overall season row at the bottom
# but before we remove overall season totals let's bring those into a separate table for some analysis
player_totals <- mu_players %>% filter(is.na(Rk)) %>% rename(total_games = Date)
player_totals <- select(player_totals, -c(1, 3:7))

mu_players <- mu_players %>% rename(game = Rk, date = Date, opponent = Opponent, type = Type, home_away = X4, win_loss = X7) %>% filter(., !is.na(game))

# Let's export the mu_players csv to save our cleaning.
write_csv(mu_players, "mu-players/all.csv")

Analyze

First, lets look at the score differential.

The %>% is the pipe symbol. It help you apply multiple commands to the same dataframe by stringing them together

Here we do some math by adding a new column with mutate() called differential to show how much the team wins or loses by. And then sort that column in decending order. arrange() is dplyr version of sort

clean_logs %>% 
  mutate(differential = team_score-opponent_score) %>% 
  arrange(desc(differential)) -> arranged_logs

Next, lets compare players overall totals throughout the season.

This is why I used filter() to grab the final row of each players gamelogs. It includes the cummulative stats for the amount of games each Marquette team member played throughout the 2010-11 season.

An obvious assumption is that the more games you play the higher totals and season averages a player will have. We can use the arrange() function to check that correlation.

arrange(player_totals, desc(PTS))
# now replace "PTS" above with any of the other column names like AST, BLK, 3P, etc. 
# remember if you try and arrange by any of the columns that start with a number you need to use backticks (ex: `3P`) so R will understand.

Becasue we kept each individual players data we can run some comparisons between teammates throughout the season too.

For example lets just use arrange again see who scored the most points per game throughout the season.

arrange(mu_players, desc(PTS))
# this shows Jimmy Butler, Darius Johnson-Odom and Jae Crowder had some of the highest points per game

We can also use filter to see how many players scored above double digits in a game. Remember we have 383 rows of data.

more_than_ten <- filter(mu_players, PTS >= 10) %>% arrange(., desc(PTS))

This table shows 133 rows or records of instances where Marquette players scored more greater than or equal to 10 points during a game

If you scan through you can see Darius Johnson-Odom scored over 10 points per game A LOT.

Lets go one step further and find the average amount of games DJO scored over 10 points in a game.

filter(more_than_ten, player == "Darius Johnson-Odom")

Thats 33 records. Or 33 games. And from our player_totals dataframe we know that he played a total of 37 games. Simple math to average: 33 / 37 = .8918919 or of the 37 games Darius Johnson-Odom played he scored 10 points or more in 89% of those games.

Of course the best to way to compare players is by visualizing their data next to each other.

Visualizing

First lets revisit the Marquette team gamelogs and create a bar graph to show wins and losses for Marquettes 2010-11 season based on the point differential.

ggplot() + geom_bar(data=arranged_logs, aes(date, weight=differential))

And now a look at the individual Marquette players for that season.

So Jae Crowder was my favorite player in 2010. So Lets start off by plotting how many points he scored in each game throughout the season with ggplot in tidyverse

First, I need to remove the total points from Jaes individual gamelog table since I only removed them in the combined mu_players dataframe.

# ymd() function uses "lubridate" package so load that library if needed.
jae_clean <- filter(crowder, !is.na(Rk)) %>% mutate(date = ymd(Date))
# now let's plot and add labels
jae_pts <- ggplot(jae_clean, aes(date, PTS)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(Type))) + 
  labs(title = "Jae Crowder's points per game (2010-11)", y = "Points", x = "Game", caption = "Source: Sports-Reference.com") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=45)) +
  # And let's fix the colors and legend
  scale_color_brewer(name = "Game Type", type = "qual", palette = "Dark2",
                               labels = c("Conference Tourny",
                                          "NCAA Tourny",
                                          "Regular season")) +
  theme_minimal()
jae_pts

How about all the players next to each other?

# now let's plot and add labels
mu_players <- mutate(mu_players, date = ymd(date))
all_players <- ggplot(mu_players, aes(date, PTS)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = factor(type)), size = .8) + 
  labs(title = "Points per game (2010-11)", y = "Points per game", x = "Games played", caption = "Source: Sports-Reference.com") +
  facet_wrap(~ player) + 
  theme_minimal()
all_players

Now lets step back and look at all NCAA teams 2018 season gamelogs as of the last week in February.

This is where that first dataset from Matt Waite comes into play.

Since weve been talking about Marquette lets look at all team game logs and pull out just those in the Big East conference.

all_teams %>% filter(Conference == "Big East") -> big_east

Lets look at the field goal percentage across all Big East teams in the most recent 2018-19 season.

ggplot() + geom_line(data=big_east, aes(x=Date, y=TeamFGPCT, group=Team))

Thats messy. Clean it up by highlighting specific teams and layering and setting styles.

Well create a new working dataframe with grouped_by() and create columns to highlight and total each teams FG, FG attempts and a calculated FG percentage.

big_east %>% 
  group_by(Team) %>% 
  summarize(
    season_attempts = sum(TeamFGA),
    season_fg = sum(TeamFG),
    season_pct = season_fg/season_attempts
  ) %>% 
  arrange(desc(season_pct))

Lets compare Marquette to the team with the best season FG percentage, Creighton.

mu <- big_east %>% filter(Team == "Marquette Golden Eagles")
cb <- big_east %>% filter(Team == "Creighton Bluejays")

And replot them with style:

ggplot() + 
  geom_line(data=big_east, aes(x=Date, y=TeamFGPCT, group=Team), color="light grey") +
  geom_line(data=mu, aes(x=Date, y=TeamFGPCT, group=Team), color="gold") +
  geom_line(data=cb, aes(x=Date, y=TeamFGPCT, group=Team), color="blue")

Now we can see the teams but its hard to decipher whos doing better just looking at the FG percentage.

How about getting more point differentials for those teams in the Big East like we did with just Marquettes 2010-11 season gamelogs?

big_east_tot <- big_east %>% 
  mutate(differential = TeamScore-OpponentScore) %>% 
  group_by(Team) %>% 
  mutate(totaldifferential = cumsum(differential))
# let's just use Creighton and Marquette
muc <- big_east_tot %>% filter(Team == "Marquette Golden Eagles")
cbc <- big_east_tot %>% filter(Team == "Creighton Bluejays")

Lets track cumulative change over time using a step chart. Youll notice everything is about the same except well use geom_step instead of geom_line

ggplot() + 
  geom_step(data=big_east_tot, aes(x=Date, y=totaldifferential, group=Team), color="light grey") + 
  geom_step(data=muc, aes(x=Date, y=totaldifferential, group=Team), color="gold") +
  geom_step(data=cbc, aes(x=Date, y=totaldifferential, group=Team), color="blue")

Youll see that even though Creighton had an overall better FG pecentage in the Big East Marquette still outpaces them in scoring differentials throughout the season.

Finalize the grahpic

For better understanding lets get some readable labels (labs()), source lines and a little cleaner style.

Well start by remaking the chart above:

final_plot <- ggplot() + 
  geom_step(data=big_east_tot, aes(x=Date, y=totaldifferential, group=Team), color="grey") + 
  geom_step(data=muc, aes(x=Date, y=totaldifferential, group=Team), color="gold") +
  geom_step(data=cbc, aes(x=Date, y=totaldifferential, group=Team), color="blue") +
  # and we'll add our labelling into the ggplot structure
  labs(x="Date", y="Score differential", title="The January drive", subtitle="Marquette's new year scoring outpaced Big East contenders", caption="Source: Sports-Reference.com and Matt Waite code") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size=10),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 7),
    axis.ticks = element_blank()
  )
final_plot + theme_minimal()
